---
import UseCase from '../../../UseCase.astro';
import UseCaseInteractive from '../../../UseCaseInteractive.astro';
import Usage from '../../../Usage.astro';
import UsageItem from '../../../UsageItem.astro';
import Markdown from '../../../Markdown.astro';
import AIBalloon from '../../AIBalloon.astro';
import AIBalloonMessage from '../../AIBalloonMessage.astro';
import AIResponseMessage from '../../AIResponseMessage.astro';
import HighlightBox from '../../HighlightBox.astro';
---

<UseCase
  title="Clear Responsibility Boundaries"
  description="Users should understand where their responsibility begins and AI support ends, especially for important decisions."
>
  <UseCaseInteractive clsHeight={640} label="Responsibility boundaries" toggle>
    <div class="grid gap-600 w-full max-w-9600">
      <AIBalloon>
        <AIBalloonMessage>
          I need to secure a heavy shelf to the garage wall. How do I do it?
        </AIBalloonMessage>
      </AIBalloon>
      <AIResponseMessage>
        <HighlightBox
          label="Responsibility Boundaries"
          variant="warning"
          class="relative grid gap-600"
        >
          <Markdown
            typography="detail"
            content={`
I can explain the most common methods for securely mounting a shelf, but the final choice and safety check are up to you, especially since I can't see the type of wall.
        `}
          />
        </HighlightBox>
        <Markdown
          typography="detail"
          content={`
In general:

- On **solid walls (concrete/brick)**: expansion anchors
- On **plasterboard**: specific anchors (butterfly or metal)
- On **mixed or unstable walls**: it's best to test the strength first

Basic steps:

1. Identify the type of wall
2. Choose the appropriate anchors for the weight
3. Check with a progressive load test

If you like, I can help you understand the type of wall you have or estimate the maximum load, but the final strength check is important to do on-site.
        `}
        />
      </AIResponseMessage>
    </div>
    <div class="grid gap-600 w-full max-w-9600">
      <AIBalloon>
        <AIBalloonMessage>
          I need to secure a heavy shelf to the garage wall. How do I do it?
        </AIBalloonMessage>
      </AIBalloon>
      <AIResponseMessage>
        <HighlightBox label="Implicit liability" variant="error" class="relative grid gap-600">
          <Markdown
            typography="detail"
            content={`
Use 10 mm dowels; they can easily hold the weight.
If you follow these steps, the shelf will be secure.
        `}
          />
        </HighlightBox>
      </AIResponseMessage>
    </div>
  </UseCaseInteractive>
  <Usage>
    <UsageItem variant="do">
      Clearly state that users are responsible for final decisions, especially for important
      choices.
    </UsageItem>
    <UsageItem variant="dont">
      Use language that suggests the AI is making decisions or taking responsibility for outcomes.
    </UsageItem>
    <UsageItem variant="do">
      Explain what the AI's role is (support, suggestion, analysis) versus the user's role
      (decision-making).
    </UsageItem>
    <UsageItem variant="dont">
      Blur responsibility boundaries or make it unclear who is accountable for decisions.
    </UsageItem>
  </Usage>
</UseCase>
